<div class="case-story__chapter">
  <h2>Redesign</h2>
  <p>The main view consolidates two screens. It allows a comprehensive view of all alerts in both map and list form. Once a user taps into an alert, they access more information about it.</p>
  <figure class="full-bleed">
    <img src="/assets/placeholder-2000.svg" data-src="assets/view-alert-flow.png" />
  </figure>
  <p>While each precinct has different data formats and requirements for it's alerts, I was able to determine a common baseline of info: location, priority, and time.</p>
  <p>This information was reliable and predictable, which allowed me to confidently style it to be easily scannable. Less predictable content was presented in a more flexible (albeit less eye-catching) way beneath the primary action buttons.</p>
  <h3>Adding info</h3>
  <p>Users can add markers with information &mdash; important for marking entrance points, water sources, and hazards. Users can precisely position the map, choose from a set of icons, and add text.</p>
  <figure class="full-bleed">
    <img src="/assets/placeholder-2000.svg" data-src="assets/add-pin-flow.png" />
  </figure>
</div>


